e? France, Great Britain, and the Question of German Unification, 1989–1990 -- t12. Franco-Soviet Relations, German Unification, and the End of the Cold War -- tPart VI. Enduring Concerns: Anschluss, Borders, And The Two Germanys -- t13. Toward a New Anschluss? France and the German and Austrian Questions, 1945−1955 -- t14. France, Poland, and Germany’s Eastern Border, 1945–1990: Th e Recurrent Issue of the German Question in French-Polish Relations -- t15. A Surprising Continuity: Th e French Attitude and Policy toward the German Democratic Republic, 1949–1990 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the immediate aftermath of World War Two, the victors were unable to agree on Germany’s fate, and the separation of the country—the result of the nascent Cold War—emerged as a de facto, if provisional, settlement. Yet East and West Germany would exist apart for half a century, making the "German question" a central foreign policy issue—and given the war-torn history between the two countries, this was felt no more keenly than in France. Drawing on the most recent historiography and previously untapped archival sources, this volume shows how France’s approach to the German question was, for the duration of the Cold War, both more constructive and consequential than has been previously acknowledged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCold War. 0aGerman reunification question (1949-1990) 0aGerman reunification question (1949-1990). 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aEast Germany.  aEurope.  aFrance.  aWest Germany.1 aAngerer, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadalassi, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Françoise, eco